              "text": "4. _012 MLP - How it Works\nThis deck explains the mechanics of a basic feedforward neural network using a multilayer perceptron (MLP). The core ideas are layers,\nweights, bias, activation, loss, backpropagation, vectorization, and gradient descent.\nLayer type\nRole\nInput layer\nReceives raw features. Each input neuron corresponds to a feature.\nHidden layer(s)\nPerform weighted transformations and nonlinear activations. More hidden\nlayers allow more complex representations.\nOutput layer\nProduces final classification, regression value, detection result, or generated\noutput.\nSource diagram - Slide 4: input, hidden, output layers\nHow to read it: Read left to right. Inputs connect to hidden neurons through weighted links, hidden neurons connect to output neurons, and every link has a\nlearnable weight. This is the basic MLP structure.\nSource diagram - Slide 7: simple MLP example\nHow to read it: The +1 nodes represent bias inputs. The network maps features x1, x2, x3 through a hidden layer to an output h. Bias lets the neuron shift its\ndecision threshold.",
