              "title": "6. _014 The Agentic AI Revolution",
              "page": 20,
              "text": "6. _014 The Agentic AI Revolution\nThis deck shifts from models that answer one input to agents that pursue goals across time. The exam focus is what makes a system an\nagent: perception, state/memory, reasoning, planning, action, learning, autonomy, and tool use.\nTraditional software\nAgentic AI system\nExecutes predefined instructions.\nPursues goals and chooses actions.\nUsually stateless or limited state.\nMaintains memory/state across interactions.\nReactive input-output behavior.\nReactive and proactive behavior.\nFixed workflows.\nCan plan, adapt, and use tools.\nPredictable deterministic pathways.\nMakes decisions under uncertainty.\n6.1 Traits and definition of agents\nTrait\nMeaning\nAutonomy\nCan operate without continuous human guidance.\nPersistence\nMaintains state/memory over time.\nReactivity\nResponds to environment changes.\nProactiveness\nInitiates actions based on goals.\nAdaptability\nLearns from experience and modifies behavior.\nGoal-orientation\nPlans and reasons to reach objectives.\nExam-important: An agent is not just a chatbot. A real agent senses/perceives, keeps state, reasons, plans, acts through tools/APIs, and learns\nfrom outcomes.\n6.2 Agent history and evolution\nSource diagram - Slide 10: evolutionary trajectory\nHow to read it: The diagram moves from rule-based systems to classical ML, deep learning, LLM agents, and AutoGen-style agent systems. The right side adds goal-\noriented behavior and autonomous agent capabilities.\nEra\nMain capability\nLimitation\n1970s-1980s rule systems\nExpert systems like MYCIN used logic rules.\nBrittle and narrowly scoped.\n1990s classical ML\nDecision trees/SVMs improved pattern\nrecognition.\nTask-specific and mostly stateless.\n2010s deep learning\nStrong perception: speech, images, translation.\nMostly reactive input-output models.\n2020s+ LLMs and agents\nLanguage reasoning, few-shot learning, tool use,\nplanning.\nNeed memory, verification, orchestration, and\nsafety controls.\n6.3 Agent architecture and cognitive loop\n•\nAgent architecture separates concerns: perception, planning, memory, execution/action, and learning.",
