              "id": "blockchain-t02-c01",
              "title": "1. Blockchain Overview",
              "page": 3,
              "text": "1. Blockchain Overview\n1.1 Origin of Bitcoin and blockchain\nThe blockchain module begins with Satoshi Nakamoto's 2008 paper, \"Bitcoin: A Peer-to-Peer Electronic\nCash System.\" Bitcoin became operational in 2009. The individual building blocks were not all new; the\ninnovation was combining peer-to-peer networking, cryptography, a decentralized distributed ledger,\nproof-of-work, and economic incentives into one working system.\nThe main motivation is direct online payment without a financial institution. Digital signatures authorize\npayments, while a peer-to-peer timestamp/proof-of-work chain prevents double spending without relying\non a central clearing party.\n1.2 Peer-to-peer network\nA peer-to-peer network is a network of independent computers that share data without a central server.\nEach peer can provide services and consume services. In blockchain, this supports decentralization\nbecause nodes can independently store, verify, and propagate transactions and blocks.\n1.3 Bitcoin block structure\nA Bitcoin block has a general structure plus a fixed 80-byte header. The header is the part miners hash\nduring proof-of-work.\nBlock component\nPurpose\nSize\nMagic number\nIdentifies the Bitcoin network; slide shows 0xD9B4BEF9.\n4 bytes\nBlock size\nNumber of bytes up to the end of the block.\n4 bytes\nBlock header\nMetadata for linking, mining, and validation.\n80 bytes\nTransaction counter\nNumber of transactions in the block.\n1-9 bytes\nTransactions\nActual transaction records.\nVariable\nHeader field\nPurpose\nSize\nVersion\nBlock version/rules.\n4 bytes\nPrevious block hash\nLinks this block to the previous block.\n32 bytes\nMerkle root\nHash summary of all transactions in the block.\n32 bytes\nTimestamp\nApproximate block time.\n4 bytes\nDifficulty bits\nCompact form of the proof-of-work target.\n4 bytes\nNonce\nValue miners change while searching for a valid hash.\n4 bytes\nExam-important: previous block hash creates the chain; Merkle root protects transactions;\nnonce is changed during mining.\nExam-important: Bitcoin is not just \"cryptography.\" It is cryptography + P2P networking +\nproof-of-work + distributed ledger + consensus rules.",
