              "id": "blockchain-t03-c01",
              "title": "2. Bitcoin Proof-of-Work Algorithm",
              "page": 9,
              "text": "2. Bitcoin Proof-of-Work Algorithm\n2.1 Meaning of proof-of-work\nProof-of-work is evidence that a miner spent computational effort. In Bitcoin, the miner searches for a block\nheader hash that is numerically less than a target.\n2.2 Target and difficulty\nThe challenge is to produce a hash below a pre-specified target. A higher target means easier mining; a\nlower target means harder mining. Therefore, target and difficulty are inversely related.\n2.3 What gets hashed?\nThe string hashed by the miner is the block header plus a nonce. Nonce means \"number once.\" In practice,\nminers repeatedly change the nonce and other mutable block data until the hash satisfies the target.\nImportant diagram: target calculation from difficulty bits.\n2.4 Toy SHA-256 run\nThe slides show a toy example where the text \"I am Mohammed ELAffendi\" is concatenated with nonce\nvalues 0 through 19. Each nonce produces a completely different SHA-256 hash. The point is\nunpredictability: miners cannot know the winning nonce in advance; they must trial many values.\nh a s h _ r e s u l t = h a s h l i b . s h a 2 5 6 ( s t r ( h e a d e r ) + s t r ( n o n c e ) ) . h e x d i g e s t ( )\nHow to read it: target = 2^(256 - difficulty_bits). A valid block hash must be numerically below this target.\nIncreasing difficulty_bits lowers the target and makes success rarer.\nt e x t = \" I a m M o h a m m e d E L A f f e n d i \"\nf o r n o n c e i n x r a n g e ( 2 0 ) :\ni n p u t = t e x t + s t r ( n o n c e )\nh a s h = h a s h l i b . s h a 2 5 6 ( i n p u t ) . h e x d i g e s t ( )\np r i n t i n p u t , ' = > ' , h a s h",
