              "page": 10,
              "text": "CS496 Blockchain Module - Exam-Ready Inline Diagram Guide\nPage 10\nImportant diagram: toy SHA-256 nonce output table.\n2.5 Leading zero bits and time doubling\nThe slides test difficulty from 0 to 31 bits. Difficulty is explained as leading bits/leading-zero-style\nconstraints in the resulting hash. Each added difficulty bit roughly halves the acceptable hash space, so\nexpected computation time roughly doubles.\n2.6 Difficulty adjustment\nProof-of-work has a timing role: it keeps Bitcoin's heartbeat near 10 minutes per block. Every 2,016 blocks,\nnodes retarget difficulty by comparing actual time against expected time.\nIf blocks were found faster than every 10 minutes on average, difficulty increases and target decreases. If\nblocks were found slower than expected, difficulty decreases and target increases.\nHow to read it: the same text with nonce 0, 1, 2, ... gives completely different hashes. This is why mining is\ntrial-and-error, not direct calculation.\n2 , 0 1 6 b l o c k s * 1 0 m i n u t e s = 2 0 , 1 6 0 m i n u t e s\nExam-important: increasing difficulty by one bit approximately doubles the computational\nwork.",
