              "id": "blockchain-t04-c01",
              "title": "3. How Bitcoin Works: A Transaction Journey",
              "page": 11,
              "text": "3. How Bitcoin Works: A Transaction Journey\n3.1 Network structure and coffee example\nThe Bitcoin transaction journey starts from a user-facing payment situation, such as buying coffee. The\ncustomer can pay in fiat dollars or in BTC/satoshis. The important point is that the wallet hides most\ntransaction construction details from the user.\nSlide image: Bitcoin network overview.\n3.2 What a transaction means\nA transaction tells the network that the owner of some bitcoin value has authorized transferring that value\nto another owner. The new owner can later create another transaction, forming a chain of ownership.\n3.3 Inputs, outputs, change, and fee\nBitcoin uses the UTXO model: unspent transaction outputs are consumed as inputs and new outputs are\ncreated. A transaction often has a change output back to the sender. The fee is the difference between\ntotal inputs and total outputs.\nPart\nMeaning\nInputs\nPrevious unspent outputs being spent.\nOutputs\nNew spendable outputs created by this transaction.\nChange output\nLeftover value returned to the sender.\nFee\nTotal inputs minus total outputs. Paid to the miner/validator in Bitcoin mining context.\nSlide example: inputs of 0.10 + 0.20 + 0.10 + 0.15 BTC total 0.55 BTC; outputs of 0.10 + 0.20 + 0.20 total\n0.50 BTC; difference is a 0.05 BTC fee.",
