              "text": "6. Ethereum Smart Contracts Practice Sheet\n6.1 Smart contract definition\nA smart contract is self-executing code stored on the Ethereum blockchain. Once deployed, it runs as\nwritten. It can automate payments, escrow, supply chain actions, insurance claims, and other\nif-condition-then-action workflows. The vending machine analogy is: if condition A is met, perform action B.\n6.2 Architecture: how execution flows\nThe practice sheet architecture shows two paths: a state-changing transaction path and a read-only call\npath.\nSmart contract architecture diagram from the practice sheet.\nStep\nMeaning\n1. Solidity source\nDeveloper writes a .sol file.\n2. Compiler solc\nCompiles to ABI + EVM bytecode.\n3. Deploy transaction\nDeploys the contract to the Ethereum network.\n4. Permanent address\nThe contract receives an address.\n5. EVM execution\nBytecode runs in an isolated sandbox.\n6. State change\nStorage/balances update if transaction succeeds.\n7. Events and receipt\nEvents are logged; receipt records success/revert and gas used.\nRead path\nview/pure function via eth_call reads state and returns decoded data without gas cost to the\ncaller off-chain.\n6.3 SimpleStorage\nSimpleStorage is the \"Hello World\" of smart contracts: it stores and retrieves a number on-chain.",
