              "id": "blockchain-t09-c01",
              "title": "8. Solana: Proof of History and Fast Transaction",
              "page": 30,
              "text": "8. Solana: Proof of History and Fast Transaction\nProcessing\n8.1 Third-generation blockchain context\nThe Solana deck frames newer blockchain systems as third/fourth generation designs that address older\nlimitations using innovations such as sharding, zero-knowledge proofs, hybrid consensus, faster/greener\noperation, and better interoperability. Solana is presented as a high-throughput chain using Proof of\nHistory plus Proof of Stake.\n8.2 What Solana is\nSolana is a high-performance public blockchain supporting smart contracts, decentralized applications, and\ndigital assets. It prioritizes speed, throughput, and cost to provide a Web2-like user experience. The slides\ncompare Solana's theoretical 65,000 TPS to Ethereum's lower base-layer throughput.\n8.3 Story\nSolana's story starts in 2017 with Anatoly Yakovenko and the Proof of History concept. Solana Labs was\nestablished in 2017, testnets followed, and mainnet beta launched in 2020 after public/private funding\nrounds.\n8.4 Solana Proof of Stake\nSOL holders can delegate their stake to validators. Validators create new blocks, secure the network, earn\nSOL rewards, and share rewards with delegators. The slides emphasize high validator hardware\nrequirements: about 256 GB RAM, a 12-core CPU, and over 1 TB storage.\nImportant diagram: Solana PoS, validator hardware, and superminority note.\n8.5 Proof of History\nProof of History is Solana's cryptographic clock. Transactions/events are placed into a sequence of\nSHA-256 hashes, giving them a verifiable order without validators constantly communicating to decide\nwhich event came first.\nThe slide also notes a \"superminority\": 21 validators controlling more than 33% of total stake. This matters\nbecause one-third stake thresholds are important for BFT-style liveness/security analysis.",
