              "title": "Important diagram: Proof of History + Tower BFT relationship.",
              "page": 31,
              "text": "CS496 Blockchain Module - Exam-Ready Inline Diagram Guide\nPage 31\nImportant diagram: Proof of History + Tower BFT relationship.\n8.6 Tower BFT\nThe slides describe Tower BFT as a Byzantine Fault Tolerance consensus system that helps validators\nagree even if some nodes fail or behave maliciously. Validators vote on new blocks, and blocks are added if\nat least about 66% of validators approve them, according to the slide.\n8.7 Proof of History transaction process\n1 User submits a trade transaction to exchange Token A for Token B.\n2 Transaction enters the PoH sequence.\n3 It is hashed into Solana's ongoing SHA-256 chain and receives a verifiable timestamp.\n4 The timestamp proves relative order without an external clock.\n5 Validators can pre-order transactions without wasting time on ordering communication.\n6 PoS + Tower BFT handles final agreement and confirmation.\n7 Trade finalizes and settles faster than traditional blockchains requiring more coordination.\n8.8 Firedancer and Alpenglow\nThe slides mention two major upgrades. Firedancer is an independent validator client developed by Jump\nCrypto, intended to improve performance and client diversity. Alpenglow is a proposed consensus overhaul\nintended to sharply reduce finality latency; the Solana forum proposal describes roughly 100-150 ms\nlatency targets.\n8.9 Other third-generation chains mentioned\nExam-important: PoH is not consensus by itself. It provides ordering/time. Solana still uses\nstake-weighted validator voting/Tower BFT-style consensus for agreement.\nHow to read it: PoH gives each event a cryptographic place in time; Tower BFT/PoS voting decides\nagreement/finality.\nTreat slide performance numbers as time-sensitive. For exams, focus on what each upgrade is\nmeant to do: Firedancer = validator client/performance/client diversity; Alpenglow =\nconsensus/finality redesign.",
