              "id": "blockchain-t10-c01",
              "title": "9. Polkadot: Blockchain of Blockchains",
              "page": 33,
              "text": "9. Polkadot: Blockchain of Blockchains\n9.1 In a nutshell\nPolkadot is a decentralized, scalable, interoperable blockchain network built around a central Relay Chain\nand connected parachains. It supports custom blockchains while maintaining shared security and\ninteroperability. DOT is used for governance, staking, and network security/resource access. The deck also\nemphasizes forkless upgrades, democratic governance, and Nominated Proof of Stake.\n9.2 Story\nThe deck says the Web3 Foundation, co-founded by Gavin Wood, held a 2017 ICO raising about $144\nmillion. About $90 million was frozen due to a Parity wallet vulnerability, but the project continued.\nPolkadot's genesis block launched in 2020. Polkadot v1 focused on the main architecture; Polkadot 2.0\nrepresents a more mature upgraded stage.\n9.3 Main components\nComponent\nMeaning\nRelay Chain\nMain chain coordinating the system, interoperability, consensus, and shared security.\nParachains\nIndependent specialized blockchains connected to the Relay Chain; can have their own tokens and\nlogic.\nBridges\nSpecial parachains/connections allowing communication with external blockchains such as\nEthereum.\nImportant diagram/text slide: Polkadot Relay Chain, parachains, and bridges.\n9.4 DOT token functions\nFunction\nMeaning\nGovernance\nDOT holders vote on fees, auctions, parachain changes, and protocol changes.\nStaking\nDOT is locked to support network operations, validator/nominator selection, and\nsecurity.\nHow to read it: Relay Chain coordinates and secures; parachains are specialized parallel chains; bridges\nconnect to external chains.",
