              "text": "2. _000 - Quantum & AGI Computing: Course\nOverview\nThis deck frames quantum computing as one part of the broader CS496 theme: AGI, Agentic AI, and\nblockchain. The quantum part begins with the difference between classical bits and qubits, then\nintroduces superposition and entanglement.\nCore ideas\nG\nClassical bit: one definite value, 0 or 1.\nG\nQubit: quantum information unit that can be in a superposition of basis states before measurement.\nG\nSuperposition: a qubit can have amplitudes for both |0> and |1>.\nG\nEntanglement: multiple qubits can share a joint state whose information is not separable into\nindependent qubit states.\nG\nAGI context: the slides place quantum computing beside Agentic AI and blockchain as pillars in a\nfuture intelligent computing stack.\n|ψ> = α|0> + β|1>\nP(0) = |α|^2,  P(1) = |β|^2,  |α|^2 + |β|^2 = 1\nDiagram: AI-agent feedback loop from the course overview (_000 slide 5).\nHow to read it: The agent observes an environment, takes an action, receives feedback/reward, and updates behavior.\nThis is not a quantum circuit, but it explains why the course connects quantum computing to autonomous intelligent\nsystems.\nExam-important\nDo not say quantum computers are fast just because they try all answers independently. The useful\nadvantage comes from superposition plus controlled interference, entanglement, and measurement\nthat amplifies useful answers and suppresses wrong ones.",
