              "page": 5,
              "text": "CS496 Quantum Computing Inline Diagrams\nPage 5\nQuantum mechanics roots\nQuantum computing is grounded in the rules used to describe photons, electrons, atoms, and\nsubatomic particles. The deck emphasizes that human-scale intuition is often misleading; the\nmathematics is the reliable guide.\nQuantization, uncertainty, and coherence\nG\nQuantization: certain physical quantities come in discrete units rather than arbitrary continuous\nvalues. Example: electrons occupy allowed energy/orbital states.\nG\nUncertainty: some pairs of quantities, such as position and momentum, cannot both be known\nexactly at the same time.\nG\nCoherence: a quantum system maintains phase relationships that make superposition and\ninterference possible. Noise, heat, vibration, and measurement can destroy coherence.\nDiagram: Quantization, uncertainty, and coherence (_001 slide 4).\nHow to read it: Read this as the three physics requirements behind qubits: discrete state structure, limits on\nsimultaneous measurement knowledge, and protected phase relationships.\nExam-important\nCoherence is the condition that lets quantum behavior stay usable. Decoherence is the loss of that\nbehavior due to interaction with the environment; it is one of the biggest practical barriers in quantum\nhardware.\nWavefunction and probabilities\nThe wavefunction describes the quantum state. Its amplitudes are not probabilities directly;\nprobabilities come from squared magnitudes of amplitudes.\nSingle qubit state:\n|ψ> = α|0> + β|1>\nNormalization:\n|α|^2 + |β|^2 = 1\nMeasurement probabilities:\nP(0) = |α|^2,  P(1) = |β|^2",
