              "id": "quantum-computing-t13-c02",
              "title": "Page 61 study notes",
              "page": 61,
              "text": "CS496 Quantum Computing Inline Diagrams\nPage 61\nTerm\nShort definition\nQubit\nQuantum bit. Before measurement, a qubit can be a superposition α|0> + β|1>.\nAmplitude\nComplex coefficient of a basis state. Probability is squared magnitude of amplitude.\nSuperposition\nLinear combination of basis states.\nMeasurement\nProcess that returns a classical outcome according to probabilities and changes the state.\nCoherence\nStable phase relationship that allows interference and superposition.\nDecoherence\nLoss of quantum behavior due to unwanted interaction/noise.\nEntanglement\nMulti-qubit state not separable into individual qubit states.\nTensor product\nMathematical operation for combining quantum systems.\nUnitary gate\nReversible operation that preserves total probability.\nHadamard H\nCreates equal superposition and enables interference.\nPauli-X\nBit-flip gate, quantum NOT.\nPauli-Z\nPhase-flip gate: |1> gets a minus sign.\nPhase gate\nChanges relative phase without changing immediate measurement probabilities.\nCNOT / CX\nControlled-X: flips target when control is |1>.\nToffoli / CCX\nTwo-control X gate; reversible AND/carry logic.\nBell state\nMaximally entangled two-qubit state.\nNo-cloning theorem\nUnknown quantum states cannot be copied perfectly.\nQuantum teleportation\nTransfer of an unknown state using entanglement, measurement, classical bits, and correction\ngates.\nOracle\nBlack-box operation encoding a problem. Often marks states by phase.\nPhase kickback\nFunction value appears as a phase on the input register.\nQFT\nQuantum Fourier Transform; converts periodic structure into frequency/phase information.\nPeriod/order r\nSmallest positive r such that a^r ≡ 1 mod N.\nDiffusion operator\nGrover operator D=2|s><s|-I that reflects amplitudes around the average.\nAmplitude amplification\nRepeated oracle+diffusion process that increases marked-state probability.\nRipple carry\nCarry-out of one bit becomes carry-in to the next bit.",
