              "page": 62,
              "text": "14. Possible exam questions with answers\n1. What makes a qubit different from a classical bit?\nA bit has one definite value, 0 or 1. A qubit can be α|0> + β|1>, and measurement returns outcomes\nwith probabilities |α|^2 and |β|^2.\n2. Why must |α|^2 + |β|^2 = 1?\nBecause total probability of all measurement outcomes must be 1.\n3. What does the Hadamard gate do?\nIt maps |0> to (|0>+|1>)/sqrt(2) and |1> to (|0>-|1>)/sqrt(2), creating equal superposition with phase\ndifference.\n4. What is the correct CNOT rule?\nThe target flips if and only if the control qubit is |1>.\n5. What is an entangled state?\nA multi-qubit state that cannot be written as a tensor product of separate one-qubit states.\n6. Write the four Bell states.\nΦ+ = (|00>+|11>)/sqrt(2), Φ- = (|00>-|11>)/sqrt(2), Ψ+ = (|01>+|10>)/sqrt(2), Ψ- =\n(|01>-|10>)/sqrt(2).\n7. How is the first Bell state created from |00>?\nApply H to the first qubit, then CNOT with the first qubit as control and the second as target.\n8. Why does teleportation not allow faster-than-light communication?\nBob cannot recover the state until Alice sends two classical bits; classical communication is\nspeed-limited.\n9. What is the no-cloning theorem and how does teleportation respect it?\nUnknown quantum states cannot be copied. Teleportation destroys Alice's original through\nmeasurement while Bob receives the state after correction.\n10. What is the quantum part of Shor's algorithm?\nEfficient period finding for f(x)=a^x mod N, using modular exponentiation and QFT.\n11. Factor 15 using a=2 in Shor-style logic.\n2^4 mod 15 = 1, so r=4. a^(r/2)=4. gcd(3,15)=3 and gcd(5,15)=5. Factors are 3 and 5.\n12. What does QFT do conceptually?",
