              "id": "quantum-computing-t15-c02",
              "title": "13. What speedup does Grover provide?",
              "page": 63,
              "text": "CS496 Quantum Computing Inline Diagrams\nPage 63\nIt transforms amplitude patterns into frequency/phase information and is especially useful for detecting\nperiodicity.\n13. What speedup does Grover provide?\nIt reduces unstructured search from O(N) to O(sqrt(N)).\n14. What does Grover's oracle do?\nIt flips the phase of the marked state while leaving unmarked states unchanged.\n15. What does the diffusion operator do?\nIt reflects amplitudes around the average, amplifying the marked state after the oracle phase flip.\n16. What problem does Deutsch-Jozsa solve?\nIt decides whether a promised Boolean function is constant or balanced.\n17. What measurement result means Deutsch-Jozsa is constant?\nAll zeros in the input register after the final Hadamards.\n18. Which gates implement a ripple-carry adder?\nCNOT gates implement XOR/sum behavior; Toffoli gates implement AND/carry behavior; X gates\nprepare input bits.\n19. Why are phase gates important if measurement probabilities do not\nimmediately change?\nBecause relative phase controls later interference, which changes final measurement probabilities.\n20. What is the role of controlled gates in algorithms?\nThey condition operations on other qubits and are essential for entanglement, oracles, arithmetic, and\nreversible logic.",
